US scientists used DNA testing to trace poached elephant tusks, aiming to combat the illegal ivory trade.
They pinpointed China's economic growth as a key driver of the black-market ivory trade, emphasizing the need for strict enforcement and education.
The recent seizure of a large ivory shipment highlights the urgency of the situation, with Kenya and Mali proposing a 20-year ban on elephant tusks trade.
Meanwhile, South Africa considers measures like contraception and culling to manage its elephant population.
The global effort to stop elephant poaching faces challenges, with some advocating for better prevention strategies over a complete ban on ivory trade.
